Personally, the two concepts which are most crucial to comprehending new software or website are, ease of use and ease of learnability.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="20" relname="span"> In some ways, both these concepts are complementary or relative to each other.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="18" relname="span"> In other words, if the software is easy to use, then this is because it is easy to learn.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="10" relname="circumstance"> When I visit a website</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="span"> and I find the comprehensive navigatibility,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="span"> then I am encouraged to venture further into the website.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="19" relname="span"> However, I believe ease of use and ease of learnibility are strongly relative to the userÂ’s level of experience with a given technology.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="12" relname="condition"> If a user is just getting onto the information superhighway,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="15" relname="span"> then their exposure and conceptual grasp of the functionality of the Internet is miniscule in focus.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="13" relname="circumstance"> Thus, when testing the users ease of use and learnibility,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="span"> it is prudent to separate groups by user experience.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="22" relname="joint"> I would like to focus on the other concepts early next week. 
